## Overview

Devscribe automates documentation generation by analyzing your connected repositories. This guide covers the complete workflow from connecting a repository to publishing your generated documentation.

## Prerequisites

Before generating documentation, ensure you have:

- An active Devscribe account with a platform created
- GitHub or GitLab repository access
- Code repository with the content you want to document

## Connecting Your Repository

### GitHub Connection

<Steps>
  <Step title="Navigate to GitHub settings">
Go to **Settings** > **GitHub** in your Devscribe dashboard.
  </Step>
  <Step title="Authorize GitHub access">
Click **Connect GitHub**. You'll be redirected to GitHub's OAuth authorization page.

<Callout type="info">
Devscribe requires repository read access to analyze your code and generate documentation.
</Callout>
  </Step>
  <Step title="Grant repository permissions">
Select the repositories you want Devscribe to access and click **Install & Authorize**.

<Callout type="success">
Once authorized, you'll see a **Reconnect GitHub** button with a check mark indicating successful connection.
</Callout>
  </Step>
</Steps>

### GitLab Connection

<Steps>
  <Step title="Navigate to GitLab settings">
Go to **Settings** > **GitLab** in your Devscribe dashboard.
  </Step>
  <Step title="Connect GitLab account">
Follow the OAuth flow to authorize Devscribe access to your GitLab groups and projects.
  </Step>
  <Step title="Select GitLab groups">
Choose which GitLab groups Devscribe should access for documentation generation.
  </Step>
</Steps>

<Callout type="tip">
You can connect both GitHub and GitLab to the same Devscribe platform.
</Callout>

## Generating Documentation

The documentation generation process follows a three-step workflow:

### Step 1: Select Documentation Type

Navigate to **Generate Docs** in your dashboard and choose your documentation type:

<CardGroup cols={3} gap="md">
  <Card title="API" icon="code">
Generate comprehensive API reference documentation from your endpoints, functions, or classes.
  </Card>
  <Card title="External" icon="book">
Create user-facing guides, tutorials, and product documentation.
  </Card>
  <Card title="Internal" icon="users">
Build internal team documentation for architecture, processes, or development guides.
  </Card>
</CardGroup>

### Step 2: Configure Source Repository

<Steps>
  <Step title="Select repository">
Choose from your connected repositories. The dropdown displays all repositories you've authorized.

<CodeSnippet language="text" title="Repository format">
organization-name/repository-name
</CodeSnippet>
  </Step>
  <Step title="Select branch">
Choose the branch to analyze. Defaults to your repository's main branch if not specified.

<Callout type="tip">
Use feature branches when documenting unreleased functionality.
</Callout>
  </Step>
  <Step title="Specify endpoint (API docs only)">
For API documentation, enter the specific endpoint or function name:

- REST endpoints: `GET /user/auth/data`
- Functions: `getUserData()`
- Classes: `AuthenticationService`

<Callout type="info">
This helps the AI focus on the specific code you want documented rather than analyzing the entire repository.
</Callout>
  </Step>
  <Step title="Add context files (optional)">
Select up to 5 files or directories to provide additional context for documentation generation.

Click **Add Context** to browse your repository file tree and select relevant files.

<Callout type="warning">
Context file limit: 5 files or paths maximum
</Callout>

**Example use cases:**
- Include related model definitions when documenting API endpoints
- Add configuration files when documenting setup processes
- Reference parent classes when documenting inherited methods
  </Step>
</Steps>

### Step 3: Generate and Edit Documentation

<Steps>
  <Step title="Enter generation prompt">
Provide specific instructions for what you want documented:

<CodeSnippet language="text" title="Example prompt for API documentation">
Document the user authentication endpoint including request parameters, response format, error codes, and authentication requirements. Include examples in cURL, Python, and JavaScript.
</CodeSnippet>

<CodeSnippet language="text" title="Example prompt for external documentation">
Create a getting started guide explaining how to install the package, configure the environment, and run the first example. Target audience is developers new to our platform.
</CodeSnippet>

<Callout type="tip">
The more specific your prompt, the better the generated documentation. Include details about target audience, required sections, and example formats.
</Callout>
  </Step>
  <Step title="Monitor generation progress">
The AI generates documentation in two phases:

1. **Thinking phase** - AI analyzes code and plans documentation structure
2. **Generation phase** - Content streams in real-time

You can view the thinking process to understand how the AI interpreted your prompt.
  </Step>
  <Step title="Review and iterate">
Once generation completes, you can:

- **Edit mode** - Make manual changes to the generated content
- **Preview mode** - View how documentation renders with Devscribe components
- **Continue generation** - Use the chat to refine and improve content

<CodeSnippet language="text" title="Example iteration prompt">
Add a troubleshooting section covering common authentication errors and their solutions.
</CodeSnippet>

<Callout type="info">
Chat history is preserved during your session, allowing iterative improvements without regenerating from scratch.
</Callout>
  </Step>
  <Step title="Set documentation title">
Enter a descriptive title for your documentation page. This title will:

- Appear in your docs.json navigation
- Be used to generate the file name
- Display as the page heading

<CodeSnippet language="text" title="Title examples">
User Authentication API
Getting Started Guide
Deployment Configuration
</CodeSnippet>

<Callout type="warning">
File names are automatically generated from titles. "User Authentication API" becomes `user_authentication_api.mdx`
</Callout>
  </Step>
  <Step title="Save documentation">
Click **Save** to persist your documentation. The system automatically:

1. Creates an `.mdx` file in your platform's `docs/generated/` directory
2. Adds frontmatter if missing (title, description, icon)
3. Updates `docs.json` with the new page entry
4. Updates `metadata.json` with file creation timestamp and hash

<Callout type="success">
Saved documentation appears immediately in your platform's file structure and is ready for deployment.
</Callout>
  </Step>
</Steps>

## Understanding docs.json

The `docs.json` file controls your documentation site's navigation structure. Every generated document must be added to `docs.json` to appear in your deployed documentation.

### File Location

<CodeSnippet language="text" title="docs.json location">
{`{platform_id}/docs/docs.json`}
</CodeSnippet>

### Basic Structure

<CodeSnippet language="json" title="docs.json">
{`{
  "name": "your-project-name",
  "favicon": "/favicon.svg",
  "navigation": {
    "tabs": [
      {
        "tab": "Guides",
        "groups": [
          {
            "group": "Get Started",
            "pages": [
              "introduction",
              "quickstart/guide"
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}`}
</CodeSnippet>

### Navigation Hierarchy

### Automatic docs.json Updates

When you save generated documentation, Devscribe automatically updates `docs.json`:

<Steps>
  <Step title="Detection of documentation type">
The system analyzes frontmatter to determine if documentation is API-related:

<CodeSnippet language="yaml" title="API documentation frontmatter">
{`---
title: "User Authentication Endpoint"
api: "POST /auth/login"
---`}
</CodeSnippet>

Documents with `api` or `openapi` fields route to the **API Reference** tab. Others route to the **Guides** tab.
  </Step>
  <Step title="Tab creation">
If the target tab doesn't exist, it's automatically created:

<CodeSnippet language="json">
{`{
  "tabs": [
    {
      "tab": "Guides",
      "groups": [{ "group": "Essentials", "pages": [] }]
    }
  ]
}`}
</CodeSnippet>
  </Step>
  <Step title="Page entry addition">
Your generated documentation is added to the first group in the target tab:

<CodeSnippet language="json">
{`{
  "groups": [
    {
      "group": "Essentials",
      "pages": [
        "introduction",
        "generated/user_authentication_api"
      ]
    }
  ]
}`}
</CodeSnippet>

<Callout type="info">
Generated pages are stored in the `generated/` directory and automatically prefixed in docs.json.
</Callout>
  </Step>
</Steps>

### Manual docs.json Management

For advanced navigation customization, manually edit `docs.json`:

<AccordionGroup>
  <Accordion title="Reorganizing page order">
  Reorder pages within the `pages` array to change sidebar display order:

  <CodeSnippet language="json">
  {`{
    "pages": [
      "introduction",
      "generated/user_authentication_api",
      "quickstart/guide"
    ]
  }`}
  </CodeSnippet>

  Pages appear in the sidebar in the order listed.
  </Accordion>
  <Accordion title="Moving pages between groups">
  Cut and paste page references between group arrays:

  <CodeSnippet language="json">
  {`{
    "groups": [
      {
        "group": "Authentication",
        "pages": ["generated/user_authentication_api"]
      },
      {
        "group": "User Management", 
        "pages": ["generated/user_profile_api"]
      }
    ]
  }`}
  </CodeSnippet>
  </Accordion>
  <Accordion title="Creating custom tabs">
  Add new tab objects for additional top-level navigation:

  <CodeSnippet language="json">
  {`{
    "tabs": [
      { "tab": "Guides", "groups": [...] },
      { "tab": "API Reference", "groups": [...] },
      { "tab": "SDK Documentation", "groups": [...] }
    ]
  }`}
  </CodeSnippet>
  </Accordion>
  <Accordion title="Adding external links">
  Use the global anchors array for external navigation links:

  <CodeSnippet language="json">
  {`{
    "navigation": {
      "tabs": [...],
      "global": {
        "anchors": [
          {
            "anchor": "Community",
            "href": "https://discord.gg/your-server",
            "icon": "discord"
          },
          {
            "anchor": "GitHub",
            "href": "https://github.com/your-org/repo",
            "icon": "github"
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  }`}
  </CodeSnippet>
  </Accordion>
</AccordionGroup>

<Callout type="warning">
Invalid `docs.json` syntax will prevent your documentation from deploying. Validate JSON structure before saving changes.
</Callout>

## Page Frontmatter Requirements

Every documentation page must include frontmatter at the top of the `.mdx` file:

<CodeSnippet language="yaml" title="Minimum frontmatter">
{`---
title: "Your Page Title"
description: "Brief description of page content"
---`}
</CodeSnippet>

<CodeSnippet language="yaml" title="Complete frontmatter options">
{`---
title: "User Authentication API"
description: "Authenticate users and manage sessions"
icon: "key"
api: "POST /auth/login"
---`}
</CodeSnippet>

<ParameterField name="title" type="string">
Page title displayed in navigation and as the H1 heading. Used to generate file names for saved documentation.
</ParameterField>

<ParameterField name="description" type="string">
Brief description for SEO and preview cards. Keep under 160 characters.
</ParameterField>

<ParameterField name="icon" type="string">
Icon displayed next to the page title in navigation. Reference [icon library](https://docs.devscribeai.com/components/icons) for available options.
</ParameterField>

<ParameterField name="api" type="string">
API method and endpoint for API reference pages. Triggers special formatting and routing to API Reference tab.
</ParameterField>

<Callout type="info">
Devscribe automatically adds frontmatter to generated documentation if missing. Manual edits may require frontmatter updates.
</Callout>

## Deploying Your Documentation

After generating and configuring documentation:

<Steps>
  <Step title="Verify docs.json entries">
Confirm all generated pages appear in your `docs.json` navigation structure.

<CodeSnippet language="bash" title="Check saved documentation">
cat {platform_id}/docs/docs.json
</CodeSnippet>
  </Step>
  <Step title="Review generated files">
Navigate to your platform's `docs/generated/` directory and verify:

- Files have correct names matching your titles
- Frontmatter includes required fields
- Content renders properly in preview mode

<Callout type="tip">
Use the Devscribe editor's preview mode to validate documentation rendering before deployment.
</Callout>
  </Step>
  <Step title="Commit and deploy">
Devscribe automatically tracks file changes via `metadata.json`. Deploy your documentation through your platform's deployment interface.

<Callout type="success">
New pages appear immediately in your deployed site once deployment completes.
</Callout>
  </Step>
</Steps>

## File Structure Reference

<CodeSnippet language="text" title="Generated documentation structure">
{`{platform_id}/
└── docs/
    ├── docs.json              # Navigation configuration
    ├── metadata.json          # File tracking and deployment status
    └── generated/             # AI-generated documentation
        ├── user_authentication_api.mdx
        ├── getting_started_guide.mdx
        └── deployment_configuration.mdx`}
</CodeSnippet>

### metadata.json

Tracks file metadata for deployment and change detection:

<CodeSnippet language="json" title="metadata.json structure">
{`{
  "lastUpdated": "2026-04-15T10:30:00Z",
  "totalFiles": 3,
  "treeStructure": {
    "generated/user_authentication_api.mdx": {
      "name": "user_authentication_api.mdx",
      "path": "generated/user_authentication_api.mdx",
      "originalHash": "abc123...",
      "currentHash": "abc123...",
      "isDeployed": true,
      "createdAt": "2026-04-15T09:00:00Z",
      "lastModified": "2026-04-15T10:30:00Z",
      "lastDeployed": "2026-04-15T10:35:00Z"
    }
  }
}`}
</CodeSnippet>

<Callout type="info">
Devscribe uses file hashes to detect changes and track deployment status. You don't need to manually edit `metadata.json`.
</Callout>

## Troubleshooting

<AccordionGroup>
  <Accordion title="Generated documentation doesn't appear in deployed site">
  **Cause:** Page not added to `docs.json` navigation

  **Solution:** Verify the page path exists in a `pages` array within `docs.json`. Check that the path matches the file name without the `.mdx` extension.

  <CodeSnippet language="json">
  {`{
    "pages": [
      "generated/your_file_name"
    ]
  }`}
  </CodeSnippet>
  </Accordion>
  <Accordion title="Repository connection fails">
  **Cause:** OAuth authorization incomplete or expired

  **Solution:** Navigate to Settings > GitHub/GitLab and click **Reconnect**. Ensure you've granted repository read permissions during authorization.
  </Accordion>
  <Accordion title="Cannot add more than 5 context files">
  **Cause:** Context file limit reached

  **Solution:** Remove less relevant context files before adding new ones. Focus on files directly related to the code being documented.
  </Accordion>
  <Accordion title="Generated file names contain unexpected characters">
  **Cause:** Special characters in page titles

  **Solution:** Devscribe automatically slugifies titles by converting to lowercase and replacing spaces with underscores. Avoid special characters like `/`, `\`, or `:` in page titles.

  <CodeSnippet language="text" title="Title transformation">
  "User Authentication: API Guide" → user_authentication_api_guide.mdx
  </CodeSnippet>
  </Accordion>
  <Accordion title="Documentation generation times out">
  **Cause:** Repository too large or context files too numerous

  **Solution:** 
  - Specify exact endpoints/functions instead of broad prompts
  - Reduce context files to essential references
  - Use smaller branches or repositories for testing
  </Accordion>
</AccordionGroup>

